<PageLayout
  title="ACTH (adrenocorticotropic hormone): the melanocortin that runs the stress axis"
  kicker="Endogenous ligand"
  description="ACTH is the one POMC peptide with its own dedicated receptor. It runs the adrenal stress axis by switching on cortisol through MC2R — but its melanocortin roots still show when levels run high and the skin darkens."
  updated="2026"
  about={[
    { name: 'Adrenocorticotropic hormone', type: 'MedicalEntity', sameAs: ['https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Adrenocorticotropic_hormone'] },
    { name: 'Melanocortin 2 receptor', type: 'MedicalEntity', sameAs: ['https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Melanocortin_2_receptor'] },
    { name: 'Proopiomelanocortin', type: 'MedicalEntity', sameAs: ['https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Proopiomelanocortin'] },
  ]}
>
  <KeyTakeaways
    items={[
      'ACTH is a 39-amino-acid peptide cut from POMC — a full member of the melanocortin family that even contains α-MSH’s active core within its sequence.',
      'It is the only natural agonist of MC2R, the melanocortin receptor found almost exclusively in the adrenal cortex, where ACTH drives the release of cortisol.',
      'MC2R cannot work alone — it needs the accessory protein MRAP to reach the cell surface and respond to ACTH, then signals through Gs → cAMP to switch on cortisol synthesis.',
      'ACTH sits at the end of the hypothalamic–pituitary–adrenal (HPA) stress axis, translating a brain stress signal into an adrenal hormone response.',
      'Because it is a melanocortin, very high ACTH also activates MC1R and darkens the skin — the bronzing seen in Addison’s disease.',
    ]}
  />

  <p>
    ACTH — adrenocorticotropic hormone — is the melanocortin that got its own job.
    Every other peptide in this family is a broad-spectrum signal read by several
    receptors, but ACTH is the one with a dedicated receptor and a single headline
    role: it runs the body's stress-hormone axis. It is still, unmistakably, a
    melanocortin — cut from the same <a href="/system">POMC</a> precursor and
    containing α-MSH's core sequence — but its day job is cortisol, not pigment.<Cite n={1} />
  </p>

  <h2>One precursor, a specialised product</h2>
  <p>
    Like <a href="/alpha-msh">α-MSH</a>, ACTH is carved out of POMC by processing
    enzymes; it is a 39-amino-acid peptide released mainly by the anterior pituitary.<Cite n={1} />
    Its sequence actually <em>contains</em> the α-MSH fragment, which is why the two
    behave like close relatives. The difference is targeting: where α-MSH ignores
    <a href="/receptors/mc2r">MC2R</a>, ACTH is the only natural key that fits it.
  </p>

  <h2>The only ligand for MC2R</h2>
  <p>
    MC2R is the odd one out among the five receptors — it lives almost exclusively in
    the adrenal cortex and responds to ACTH alone.<Cite n={1} /> It is also uniquely
    dependent: MC2R cannot even reach the cell surface without a partner protein called
    <strong>MRAP</strong> (MC2R accessory protein). Once ACTH binds the MC2R–MRAP
    complex, the receptor activates the Gs → cAMP pathway, which switches on the
    steroidogenic enzymes that manufacture <strong>cortisol</strong>.<Cite n={1} />
  </p>
  <p>
    This is the final handoff of the <strong>hypothalamic–pituitary–adrenal (HPA)
    axis</strong>: stress signals in the brain drive the pituitary to release ACTH,
    ACTH drives the adrenal to release cortisol, and cortisol raises blood glucose,
    mobilises energy, and dampens inflammation as part of the stress response.<Cite n={2} />
  </p>

  <h2>When the melanocortin roots show</h2>
  <p>
    ACTH's family resemblance becomes visible when its levels run high. Because it is a
    melanocortin, excess ACTH spills over onto <a href="/receptors/mc1r">MC1R</a>, the
    skin's pigment receptor, and darkens the skin.<Cite n={3} /> The classic example is
    <strong>Addison's disease</strong>, where failing adrenals remove cortisol's brake
    on the pituitary; ACTH climbs, and the skin takes on a characteristic bronze tone.
    It is a clean demonstration that ACTH never stopped being a melanocortin — it just
    usually keeps that side of itself in the background.
  </p>

  <h2>The honest bottom line</h2>
  <p>
    ACTH is the exception that proves the rule of this system. Where the other
    melanocortins are generalists, ACTH is a specialist with its own receptor, its own
    accessory protein, and its own axis to run. Yet the pigment darkening at high
    levels gives the game away: it is POMC's peptide for the stress response, built on
    the same chassis as the signals for skin, appetite, and inflammation. For the
    receptor's side of the story, see <a href="/receptors/mc2r">MC2R — the ACTH
    receptor</a>.
  </p>

